WEBVTT

1
00:00:02.669 --> 00:00:05.796
[crickets chirping]

2
00:00:07.000 --> 00:00:13.074
Advertise your product or brand here
contact www.OpenSubtitles.org today

3
00:00:43.377 --> 00:00:46.380
[vehicle approaching]

4
00:00:58.683 --> 00:01:00.768
[breathing heavily]

5
00:01:20.371 --> 00:01:21.539
Bullshit.

6
00:01:21.539 --> 00:01:23.748
It is this friggin' wide.

7
00:01:23.750 --> 00:01:25.251
And it's periodic.

8
00:01:25.251 --> 00:01:27.628
Bull. Shit.

9
00:01:27.629 --> 00:01:28.712
Show me.

10
00:01:28.713 --> 00:01:30.090
[both breathing heavily]

11
00:01:32.216 --> 00:01:33.343
[exhales. sniffles]

12
00:01:35.429 --> 00:01:37.014
Something terrestrial. gotta be.

13
00:01:37.890 --> 00:01:39.347
Bouncing off the moon.

14
00:01:39.348 --> 00:01:41.685
Gee. I never thought to check that.

15
00:01:42.394 --> 00:01:44.103
Look at that slope. man.

16
00:01:44.103 --> 00:01:46.021
You could ski down that thing.

17
00:01:46.022 --> 00:01:47.397
It is drifting.

18
00:01:47.399 --> 00:01:50.234
Look here. Zoom in. Zoom in.

19
00:01:50.234 --> 00:01:51.569
See that variation?

20
00:01:52.069 --> 00:01:55.489
And look. This gap here?
This is where it stops. then starts over.

21
00:01:55.490 --> 00:01:58.116
- It repeats?
- Every 78 seconds.

22
00:01:58.117 --> 00:01:59.493
The whole entire thing.

23
00:02:00.495 --> 00:02:02.831
Three hours straight. and no end in sight.

24
00:02:07.168 --> 00:02:08.169
It can't be.

25
00:02:09.419 --> 00:02:12.382
[chuckles. snorts]

26
00:02:20.473 --> 00:02:22.807
It's gotta be something
bouncing off the... off the--

27
00:02:22.808 --> 00:02:24.977
It's not bouncing off the moon. Dave.

28
00:02:24.978 --> 00:02:28.064
Well. maybe it's those Chatty Cathys
at the Forest Service.

29
00:02:28.856 --> 00:02:31.442
I hate those guys. Always on their radios.
talking about trees.

30
00:02:31.443 --> 00:02:33.527
Dave. it's not Smokey Bear
we're picking up.

31
00:02:33.528 --> 00:02:34.612
Look at that signal.

32
00:02:35.112 --> 00:02:36.198
It's drifting.

33
00:02:37.406 --> 00:02:38.491
What is it. then?

34
00:02:41.828 --> 00:02:43.163
[chuckles]

35
00:02:45.039 --> 00:02:48.210
Looks like simple pulse-width modulation.
Old-school. like Morse code.

36
00:02:49.252 --> 00:02:53.171
Maybe somehow.
it's the time signal out of Fort Collins.

37
00:02:53.173 --> 00:02:56.008
- They use pulse-width modulation.
- It's not the atomic clock.

38
00:02:56.009 --> 00:02:58.510
The atomic clock changes every minute
because it's a clock.

39
00:02:58.512 --> 00:03:01.430
This is the same exact data
repeated every 78 seconds.

40
00:03:01.431 --> 00:03:06.645
Plus. this is coming
from 600 light-years away.

41
00:03:07.854 --> 00:03:08.854
[chuckles]

42
00:03:08.855 --> 00:03:12.150
This Morse code of yours
seems to be split four ways.

43
00:03:15.361 --> 00:03:17.405
The pulses are of equal duration.

44
00:03:17.406 --> 00:03:20.240
but they're positioned
across four different frequencies.

45
00:03:20.241 --> 00:03:23.579
- [astronomer] Looks like a player piano.
- So not binary but base four.

46
00:03:24.079 --> 00:03:25.079
Quaternary.

47
00:03:25.079 --> 00:03:26.247
[groans]

48
00:03:26.831 --> 00:03:28.332
This won't be easy to crack.

49
00:03:28.834 --> 00:03:31.752
[astronomers clamoring]

50
00:03:31.752 --> 00:03:33.671
[clamoring continues]

51
00:03:36.091 --> 00:03:37.718
No. no. If you look at this. Look at...

52
00:03:39.218 --> 00:03:41.429
[Bob chuckles] What do you think it says?

53
00:03:41.430 --> 00:03:45.016
[Ray] Maybe just.
"Hello. Hey. hey. We're out here."

54
00:03:45.516 --> 00:03:48.687
What did we put on Voyagers 1 and 2?
Chuck Berry?

55
00:03:49.228 --> 00:03:51.899
Maybe this is just
their version of "Johnny B. Goode."

56
00:03:53.775 --> 00:03:56.069
Imagine the power it took to send it.

57
00:03:56.903 --> 00:03:58.570
Megawatts? [chuckles]

58
00:03:58.572 --> 00:03:59.823
Gigawatts?

59
00:04:00.699 --> 00:04:02.824
And that's if it's pointed only at us.

60
00:04:02.825 --> 00:04:04.451
Antenna the size of Africa.

61
00:04:04.453 --> 00:04:05.621
- Mm-hmm.
- Bigger.

62
00:04:07.788 --> 00:04:10.167
You go to all that trouble
to send a message.

63
00:04:10.959 --> 00:04:12.877
it's gotta be more than just "hello."

64
00:04:14.504 --> 00:04:16.838
And why make it hard to understand?

65
00:04:17.423 --> 00:04:18.466
Quaternary?

66
00:04:19.091 --> 00:04:21.552
That's like encryption.
Why would you bother to...

67
00:04:30.728 --> 00:04:32.105
It's not quaternary.

68
00:04:36.442 --> 00:04:38.069
I think I know what it is.

69
00:04:38.069 --> 00:04:40.863
[upbeat music playing]

70
00:05:14.564 --> 00:05:15.565
[rat squeaks]

71
00:05:18.776 --> 00:05:19.778
[rat squeaks]

72
00:05:21.446 --> 00:05:23.947
[Carol] <i>The twin moons hung low and full.</i>

73
00:05:23.949 --> 00:05:26.783
Two wine-green eyes
peering over the horizon

74
00:05:26.785 --> 00:05:29.204
as if to steal a glimpse
into Lucasia's soul.

75
00:05:29.954 --> 00:05:32.122
She paced the blood-soaked decks
of the <i>Mercator.</i>

76
00:05:32.124 --> 00:05:36.002
looking for something. anything.
that might take her mind off Raban.

77
00:05:36.961 --> 00:05:40.841
Ascending the forecastle. her gaze
lingered over a bare-chested young sailor.

78
00:05:41.466 --> 00:05:43.300
On hands and knees he scrubbed.

79
00:05:43.302 --> 00:05:47.723
his sinewy forearms stretched taut as he
washed away all trace of the day's fight.

80
00:05:48.432 --> 00:05:50.141
With a languid nod...

81
00:05:50.141 --> 00:05:51.893
[crowd chuckling]

82
00:05:51.894 --> 00:05:54.478
...Lucasia bade him follow to her cabin.

83
00:05:54.980 --> 00:05:58.356
Little did this callow deckhand know
that serving at his captain's pleasure

84
00:05:58.358 --> 00:06:00.192
might take on such sweet meaning.

85
00:06:00.194 --> 00:06:01.360
[crowd chuckling]

86
00:06:01.360 --> 00:06:05.447
Or. regrettably.
that it would last but a single night.

87
00:06:05.449 --> 00:06:08.201
[crowd murmuring]

88
00:06:08.201 --> 00:06:12.788
Later. at four bells.
Lucasia stood by the mizzenmast.

89
00:06:12.788 --> 00:06:15.959
Once again. she was alone.

90
00:06:17.084 --> 00:06:18.793
She pulled her topcoat tighter.

91
00:06:18.795 --> 00:06:21.923
fingering its coarse wool
as her thoughts flashed back to Raban.

92
00:06:21.923 --> 00:06:25.259
It had been he who first wrapped
the coat around her.

93
00:06:25.259 --> 00:06:27.136
whispering in her ear.

94
00:06:27.137 --> 00:06:31.598
"May this keep you warm
in my absence. <i>ma chérie</i>."

95
00:06:31.600 --> 00:06:33.100
[crowd murmuring]

96
00:06:33.100 --> 00:06:37.064
With that. Raban. proud. haughty Raban.

97
00:06:37.980 --> 00:06:40.192
mounted the plank and leaped from sight.

98
00:06:40.776 --> 00:06:43.278
The amaranthine slipsand closed over him.

99
00:06:44.571 --> 00:06:45.906
leaving nary a ripple.

100
00:06:46.572 --> 00:06:47.740
[crowd] Aw...

101
00:06:56.500 --> 00:06:58.000
[PA beeps]

102
00:06:58.000 --> 00:07:02.213
[store manager] Attention. lovers of
speculative historical romance literature.

103
00:07:02.213 --> 00:07:05.925
best-selling author Carol Sturka
will now sign her new novel.

104
00:07:05.925 --> 00:07:07.509
<i>"Bloodsong of Wycaro."</i>

105
00:07:07.511 --> 00:07:09.762
the fourth book in her
"<i>Winds of Wycaro"</i> trilogy.

106
00:07:09.762 --> 00:07:12.723
"Why-car-oh." please!
It's "Winds of Why-car-oh!"

107
00:07:12.723 --> 00:07:13.807
[crowd clamoring]

108
00:07:13.809 --> 00:07:16.060
And <i>Bloodsong</i> is the best yet.

109
00:07:16.060 --> 00:07:17.812
God. are you in for a treat.

110
00:07:17.812 --> 00:07:19.271
[crowd cheers]

111
00:07:19.273 --> 00:07:20.690
Let's go sign books!

112
00:07:23.651 --> 00:07:25.903
[Maureen] Raban is alive. right?

113
00:07:25.903 --> 00:07:27.654
Maureen. You could read it.

114
00:07:27.656 --> 00:07:29.281
[chuckles] Well. I will. Tonight.

115
00:07:29.283 --> 00:07:31.408
- I've already unplugged the phone.
- [laughs]

116
00:07:31.410 --> 00:07:33.119
Just. uh...

117
00:07:33.120 --> 00:07:35.620
- Raban's not on the cover.
- No. he's not.

118
00:07:35.622 --> 00:07:39.042
And he... he's never not been
on the cover. Carol.

119
00:07:39.584 --> 00:07:41.295
If Raban doesn't come back...

120
00:07:42.170 --> 00:07:43.422
[sighs] ...I'm done.

121
00:07:44.173 --> 00:07:45.173
[mouths] Come here.

122
00:07:46.175 --> 00:07:48.050
Page 218.

123
00:07:48.968 --> 00:07:50.512
[chuckles]

124
00:07:51.262 --> 00:07:53.764
- Okay. Thank you.
- [chuckles] Okay. Bye.

125
00:07:53.764 --> 00:07:54.932
Thanks. Maureen.

126
00:07:54.932 --> 00:07:57.685
- Okay. this is Olga.
- Hi. Hi. Olga.

127
00:07:57.685 --> 00:08:01.355
[indistinct chattering]

128
00:08:01.355 --> 00:08:03.065
- Hi. Yvette!
- [chuckles]

129
00:08:04.026 --> 00:08:05.319
Hi!

130
00:08:05.944 --> 00:08:06.987
Love it.

131
00:08:08.154 --> 00:08:11.156
- Happy reading.
- This is Nicky. with a pillow.

132
00:08:11.158 --> 00:08:13.283
- Nicky with a... Oh. my gosh!
- I made it myself.

133
00:08:13.285 --> 00:08:15.119
- Look at that. You made this?
- Yes.

134
00:08:15.120 --> 00:08:16.204
This is Christine.

135
00:08:16.204 --> 00:08:18.372
This is Paulina and support person.

136
00:08:18.372 --> 00:08:19.540
- This is Carlotta.
- Hi.

137
00:08:19.540 --> 00:08:21.250
Say. "Raban".

138
00:08:21.250 --> 00:08:23.002
Raban.

139
00:08:23.002 --> 00:08:25.420
When Raban and Eldgammel
fell in the cargo hold.

140
00:08:25.422 --> 00:08:27.380
do you remember what it was loaded with?

141
00:08:27.382 --> 00:08:28.673
Mandovian spicefruit.

142
00:08:28.675 --> 00:08:30.843
Which Lucasia is...

143
00:08:30.843 --> 00:08:32.094
[both gasp]

144
00:08:32.095 --> 00:08:33.802
[both] Deathly allergic to!

145
00:08:33.803 --> 00:08:36.264
- Oh. you guys run a fan club?
- Of course!

146
00:08:38.976 --> 00:08:40.477
- [Carol] Thank you so much!
- [superfan] Thank you.

147
00:08:40.479 --> 00:08:41.562
- Hi. Tanya.
- Hi!

148
00:08:41.562 --> 00:08:42.772
- Are you excited?
- Yes.

149
00:08:42.773 --> 00:08:44.065
- Hi. Yvonne.
- Hi.

150
00:08:44.066 --> 00:08:45.982
I got two books. one for the tub.

151
00:08:45.984 --> 00:08:49.028
This is a authentic cutlass
just like Raban's.

152
00:08:49.028 --> 00:08:50.779
- Okay.
- Careful. it's really sharp.

153
00:08:50.780 --> 00:08:52.365
Okay. so three things.

154
00:08:52.365 --> 00:08:55.659
A: When finally are they
gonna make a "<i>Wycaro"</i> movie?

155
00:08:55.661 --> 00:08:58.663
And please tell me it'll be in actual
theaters. not on the Lifetime Network.

156
00:08:58.663 --> 00:09:00.998
B: You gotta get ILM to do the slipsand.

157
00:09:00.999 --> 00:09:03.543
otherwise it's just gonna look like <i>merde</i>.
pardon my French.

158
00:09:03.543 --> 00:09:07.212
And C: A small but very crucial point.

159
00:09:07.214 --> 00:09:12.051
as a two-masted schooner. the <i>Mercator</i>
would not possess a mizzenmast. So--

160
00:09:12.052 --> 00:09:14.886
Craig. I'm gonna need you
to put this back in the bag

161
00:09:14.888 --> 00:09:16.472
before the store manager sees it.

162
00:09:17.014 --> 00:09:18.432
- Oh.
- Right.

163
00:09:18.432 --> 00:09:19.851
- Your humble servant.
- Thank you.

164
00:09:21.019 --> 00:09:23.645
- Oh. that's the one.
- [crowd clamoring]

165
00:09:23.647 --> 00:09:25.023
Thank you so much.

166
00:09:25.691 --> 00:09:27.692
- We'll see you at the next one.
- Happy reading.

167
00:09:27.692 --> 00:09:29.570
[chuckles] All right. All right.

168
00:09:33.698 --> 00:09:37.243
[driver] Hi. ladies. I have us
going to the Hyatt Regency Dallas.

169
00:09:37.244 --> 00:09:39.580
- Hi. Yeah. Thanks. uh. perfect.
- [engine starts]

170
00:09:40.163 --> 00:09:43.834
[driver] That was quite a send-off.
I'm sorry. should I know who you are?

171
00:09:45.001 --> 00:09:47.171
Uh. depends.
You a big fan of mindless crap?

172
00:09:47.921 --> 00:09:48.922
[driver chuckles]

173
00:09:49.505 --> 00:09:50.506
[sighs]

174
00:10:06.731 --> 00:10:11.653
[machine whirring]

175
00:10:14.072 --> 00:10:16.033
[door beeps. unlocks]

176
00:10:19.620 --> 00:10:20.995
[radio chatter]

177
00:10:20.995 --> 00:10:22.330
[Mel] Morning. Doc.

178
00:10:22.331 --> 00:10:24.457
Well. it certainly is.

179
00:10:25.583 --> 00:10:27.126
- Hey. Mel.
- Hey.

180
00:10:27.919 --> 00:10:29.254
Ooh. where'd those come from?

181
00:10:29.837 --> 00:10:30.838
Yours truly.

182
00:10:31.506 --> 00:10:33.673
Help yourself.
I think they're mostly glazed.

183
00:10:33.674 --> 00:10:36.760
but one box ought to be sprinkled.
powdered and all that.

184
00:10:36.761 --> 00:10:38.553
What did we do to deserve this?

185
00:10:38.554 --> 00:10:41.933
Ah. my 14-year-old's selling 'em
for marching band.

186
00:10:42.643 --> 00:10:44.601
- [door beeps]
- [Jenn] Well. aren't you a good dad.

187
00:10:44.602 --> 00:10:47.230
- What does she play?
- [Mel] Trombone.

188
00:10:48.065 --> 00:10:50.566
- [Mel] Doctor D!
- [Deshpande] Good evening.

189
00:10:50.567 --> 00:10:52.360
Morning. Whatever.

190
00:10:52.360 --> 00:10:54.653
- [Jenn] Look what Mel brought.
- [Deshpande] Ooh. for us?

191
00:10:54.654 --> 00:10:55.904
[Mel] Yeah. please.

192
00:10:55.905 --> 00:10:57.697
They got you two working late.

193
00:10:57.698 --> 00:11:00.118
[Jenn] Yeah. I gotta gas a bunch of rats.

194
00:11:01.285 --> 00:11:02.828
So. how goes the big project?

195
00:11:03.496 --> 00:11:04.539
What have you heard?

196
00:11:05.249 --> 00:11:07.125
I don't know. Things.

197
00:11:07.668 --> 00:11:09.168
Well...

198
00:11:09.168 --> 00:11:11.419
[sighs] Our team's fairly certain
we've got a sequence

199
00:11:11.421 --> 00:11:13.004
that encodes for a lysogenic virus.

200
00:11:13.005 --> 00:11:14.923
But after eight whole months
of animal testing...

201
00:11:14.924 --> 00:11:16.842
Macaques. rabbits. mice...

202
00:11:16.844 --> 00:11:19.471
- Guinea pigs.
- Guinea pigs. Now rats.

203
00:11:19.971 --> 00:11:22.057
No clinical signs whatsoever.

204
00:11:24.559 --> 00:11:25.769
[Jenn] Put another way...

205
00:11:26.602 --> 00:11:27.604
we got bubkes.

206
00:11:28.437 --> 00:11:29.523
[Deshpande] We got bubkes.

207
00:11:44.162 --> 00:11:46.748
- [sighs]
- [Jenn] Okay. how do you wanna do this?

208
00:11:47.290 --> 00:11:50.586
[Deshpande] Uh. I can put 'em to sleep
if you wanna do the cardiac sticks.

209
00:11:51.461 --> 00:11:53.671
[Jenn] I hate the cardiac sticks.

210
00:11:53.672 --> 00:11:55.923
[Deshpande] Well. you're more than welcome
to gas them.

211
00:11:56.549 --> 00:11:58.009
[Jenn] I hate gassing them.

212
00:11:58.009 --> 00:11:59.885
[Deshpande] Might be in the wrong career.

213
00:11:59.886 --> 00:12:02.471
All right. cardiac sticks it is.

214
00:12:02.471 --> 00:12:04.725
- [grunts. blows]
- Let's get it over with.

215
00:12:06.809 --> 00:12:07.811
Uh-oh.

216
00:12:09.605 --> 00:12:10.605
Check it out.

217
00:12:11.273 --> 00:12:12.399
Oh. damn.

218
00:12:13.524 --> 00:12:15.235
What do you figure happened there?

219
00:12:16.320 --> 00:12:18.572
[machine beeps. hisses]

220
00:12:21.325 --> 00:12:22.366
I don't know.

221
00:12:45.139 --> 00:12:46.600
He's looking pretty dead to me.

222
00:12:49.101 --> 00:12:50.101
You got a heartbeat?

223
00:12:50.102 --> 00:12:52.022
I can't feel jack shit in these gloves.

224
00:13:00.197 --> 00:13:01.572
Huh.

225
00:13:01.572 --> 00:13:02.783
Huh. what?

226
00:13:04.158 --> 00:13:05.576
He's absolutely got a heartbeat.

227
00:13:05.576 --> 00:13:07.702
A strong one. Just bam. bam. bam.

228
00:13:07.703 --> 00:13:09.455
It's weird.
If I didn't know any better. I'd--

229
00:13:09.456 --> 00:13:11.999
[grunts] God. Oh. shit. Oh. no.

230
00:13:12.000 --> 00:13:13.710
You've got to be kidding me.

231
00:13:15.128 --> 00:13:17.004
- Shit.
- Did he break the skin?

232
00:13:17.004 --> 00:13:19.298
Um. Yeah. I don't...
Yeah. it's through the glove.

233
00:13:19.298 --> 00:13:22.134
[Deshpande] Oh. shit. Uh. soak it quick.

234
00:13:22.134 --> 00:13:23.219
Keep it submerged.

235
00:13:23.220 --> 00:13:25.679
If it's bleeding.
make sure to squeeze it out good.

236
00:13:25.681 --> 00:13:28.642
I'm gonna call this in
as soon as I catch him. okay?

237
00:13:41.279 --> 00:13:42.613
Uh-huh.

238
00:13:42.614 --> 00:13:45.408
[muttering]

239
00:13:45.408 --> 00:13:46.743
Right there.

240
00:13:49.370 --> 00:13:51.081
[water splashing]

241
00:13:52.290 --> 00:13:54.960
Let's mark 3:36 and. uh...

242
00:13:57.879 --> 00:13:59.172
Jenn?

243
00:13:59.173 --> 00:14:00.798
[Jenn breathing shakily]

244
00:14:02.259 --> 00:14:03.967
Talk to me. Jenn. Jenn!

245
00:14:03.969 --> 00:14:05.928
Jenn! Jenn! Jenn!

246
00:14:06.971 --> 00:14:08.307
We are getting out right now.

247
00:14:09.807 --> 00:14:12.059
I got you. [grunts] Okay. come on.

248
00:14:12.936 --> 00:14:13.979
I got you.

249
00:14:18.149 --> 00:14:19.400
[grunts]

250
